00:30:28.232 --> 00:30:30.440
AUDIENCE: How does it work
with the writers on a show

00:30:30.440 --> 00:30:31.189
like "The Office"?

00:30:31.189 --> 00:30:33.340
How did you go about
creating Dwight?

00:30:33.340 --> 00:30:36.085
Was it a written part that
then you put your stamp on,

00:30:36.085 --> 00:30:37.820
or did you guys exchange ideas?

00:30:37.820 --> 00:30:41.362
How do you create that and
collaborate with the writers?

00:30:41.362 --> 00:30:43.570
RAINN WILSON: So the word
that you used, collaborate,

00:30:43.570 --> 00:30:46.162
is really the best word.

00:30:46.162 --> 00:30:48.370
I mean, there wouldn't be
Dwight without the writers,

00:30:48.370 --> 00:30:51.090
and without Greg
Daniels especially.

00:30:51.090 --> 00:30:55.150
He really is the super
genius behind the whole show.

00:30:55.150 --> 00:30:57.930
First of all, our "Office"
was based on the BBC "Office,"

00:30:57.930 --> 00:31:01.119
so Gareth was an
amazing creation.

00:31:01.119 --> 00:31:02.660
And there's just so
much stuff that I

00:31:02.660 --> 00:31:04.950
did as Dwight that
just was taken

00:31:04.950 --> 00:31:07.940
from Gareth, stolen
from Mackenzie Crook

00:31:07.940 --> 00:31:10.750
and him playing Gareth.

00:31:10.750 --> 00:31:13.130
And then I had
conversations with Greg

00:31:13.130 --> 00:31:17.150
about what he was
thinking about Dwight.

00:31:17.150 --> 00:31:19.630
He wrote a really
great email early on.

00:31:19.630 --> 00:31:20.960
I need to find that email.

00:31:23.850 --> 00:31:24.990
I wrote him an email.

00:31:24.990 --> 00:31:26.300
I said, I'm worried
that Dwight's just

00:31:26.300 --> 00:31:28.091
kind of going to be
the annoying, geeky guy

00:31:28.091 --> 00:31:29.200
in the office.

00:31:29.200 --> 00:31:32.960
What can we do to kind
of change that up,

00:31:32.960 --> 00:31:35.820
and give him more textures
and layers and nuance?

00:31:35.820 --> 00:31:39.980
And he wrote this beautiful
essay about Dwight, and how

00:31:39.980 --> 00:31:42.000
he sees the world,
and his hierarchies,

00:31:42.000 --> 00:31:46.980
and his love of order, and his
family, and stuff like that.

00:31:46.980 --> 00:31:48.910
I have to find that
essay somewhere.

00:31:48.910 --> 00:31:52.990
But for instance, early
on in the first season,

00:31:52.990 --> 00:31:55.690
there was no hint of Dwight
being on a farm or anything

00:31:55.690 --> 00:31:56.190
like that.

00:31:56.190 --> 00:31:58.130
And I did in
improvisation where I

00:31:58.130 --> 00:32:00.250
said, just completely
off the cuff, I was like,

00:32:00.250 --> 00:32:02.360
"My name is Dwight Schrute.

00:32:02.360 --> 00:32:05.240
My father's name
is Dwight Schrute.

00:32:05.240 --> 00:32:06.970
His father's name?

00:32:06.970 --> 00:32:10.790
Dwide Shrude-- Amish."

00:32:10.790 --> 00:32:13.520
And all of a sudden, there
was this Amish connection,

00:32:13.520 --> 00:32:15.390
and they were like,
oh that's cool.

00:32:15.390 --> 00:32:19.120
And that led to, eventually, the
beat farm, and the Amishness,

00:32:19.120 --> 00:32:22.410
and Mose, and the
bed and breakfast.

00:32:22.410 --> 00:32:26.417
It came out of an improv, so
there was a give and take.

00:32:26.417 --> 00:32:28.750
And that was one of the great
things about "The Office."

00:32:28.750 --> 00:32:31.370
I have a friend on a
big sitcom right now,

00:32:31.370 --> 00:32:33.490
and they're not allowed
to improvise at all.

00:32:33.490 --> 00:32:36.970
I mean, if it says, um,
uh, yeah, hello, you

00:32:36.970 --> 00:32:40.450
can't even say, um, OK, hello.

00:32:40.450 --> 00:32:42.050
You're doing a
comedy, and you have

00:32:42.050 --> 00:32:44.370
to say every line as scripted.

00:32:44.370 --> 00:32:47.840
And "The Office" was
very collaborative,

00:32:47.840 --> 00:32:49.190
which I really appreciated.

