00:32:57.090 --> 00:32:58.310
RAINN WILSON: Oh, nice.

00:32:58.310 --> 00:33:00.810
AUDIENCE: So my question is
what was your experience writing

00:33:00.810 --> 00:33:04.710
the book, taking so much time
to just reflect and look back

00:33:04.710 --> 00:33:06.880
and sort of process your life?

00:33:09.670 --> 00:33:11.980
How was the experience of
it, and has it changed at all

00:33:11.980 --> 00:33:14.580
how you live now?

00:33:18.050 --> 00:33:19.700
RAINN WILSON: That's
a good question.

00:33:19.700 --> 00:33:21.400
Technology's the
number one enemy

00:33:21.400 --> 00:33:23.300
to trying to get
anything creative done.

00:33:23.300 --> 00:33:26.210
And maybe you guys find
that-- you work in technology,

00:33:26.210 --> 00:33:29.010
but I imagine your emails
and your Twitter feed

00:33:29.010 --> 00:33:32.600
are your number one enemy to
try doing programming or design,

00:33:32.600 --> 00:33:34.780
or whatever it is you're doing.

00:33:34.780 --> 00:33:38.496
I would turn the Wi-Fi
off on my computer.

00:33:38.496 --> 00:33:40.370
What I really wanted to
do was get a computer

00:33:40.370 --> 00:33:44.290
without any Wi-Fi,
so it was just

00:33:44.290 --> 00:33:46.700
like I was-- but it was great.

00:33:46.700 --> 00:33:50.640
It was very meditative.

00:33:50.640 --> 00:33:53.190
I realized that my only
creative hours were really

00:33:53.190 --> 00:33:55.720
between like 9:00 and 12:30.

00:33:55.720 --> 00:33:58.030
After that my brain was mush.

00:33:58.030 --> 00:34:01.020
And in that period of
time, I could write

00:34:01.020 --> 00:34:07.920
between 400 and 1,000 words.

00:34:07.920 --> 00:34:12.580
If you do that every day, If
you write 1,000 words a day

00:34:12.580 --> 00:34:19.267
for 300 days, then
you've got 300,000 words.

00:34:19.267 --> 00:34:19.850
Is that right?

00:34:19.850 --> 00:34:21.330
That's too much words.

00:34:21.330 --> 00:34:24.199
See, this is why I'm
not in programming.

00:34:24.199 --> 00:34:25.240
But you can write a book.

00:34:25.240 --> 00:34:26.114
You know what I mean?

00:34:26.114 --> 00:34:27.150
You can write a book.

00:34:27.150 --> 00:34:32.449
So it was a great process of
looking back on your life.

00:34:32.449 --> 00:34:36.840
And it was the first
time I really made myself

00:34:36.840 --> 00:34:39.570
that disciplined to
sit down every day

00:34:39.570 --> 00:34:42.909
and put down those number
of words on the page.

00:34:45.960 --> 00:34:46.770
AUDIENCE: Hello.

00:34:46.770 --> 00:34:50.380
So since faith and spirituality
is a big part of your book,

00:34:50.380 --> 00:34:54.187
I was wondering what your
personal definition of God is.

00:34:54.187 --> 00:34:55.770
RAINN WILSON: That's
a great question,

00:34:55.770 --> 00:34:57.895
because I think that that's
where people get really

00:34:57.895 --> 00:34:58.625
hung up.

00:34:58.625 --> 00:35:05.520
I also joke that it's really
am anathema for a comedian

00:35:05.520 --> 00:35:08.530
to talk about God
or spirituality.

00:35:08.530 --> 00:35:11.690
First of all, other
comedians are just like, ugh.

00:35:11.690 --> 00:35:13.190
They don't know how
to deal with it.

00:35:13.190 --> 00:35:16.260
And I love talking about topics
that really clear the room,

00:35:16.260 --> 00:35:17.416
like God and death.

00:35:17.416 --> 00:35:19.290
You bring up, so what
do you think about God?

00:35:19.290 --> 00:35:21.930
Uh, excuse me, I got to go.

00:35:21.930 --> 00:35:25.070
It really creeps people out.

00:35:25.070 --> 00:35:27.410
Recently, I said on one
of these book tour things,

00:35:27.410 --> 00:35:30.530
the most punk rock thing
that someone could do

00:35:30.530 --> 00:35:32.320
is talk about God
and spirituality.

00:35:32.320 --> 00:35:35.430
Because it is the thing that
just unsettles people more

00:35:35.430 --> 00:35:36.345
than anything else.

00:35:36.345 --> 00:35:38.470
But one of the things we
tried to do at SoulPancake

00:35:38.470 --> 00:35:41.262
was really redefine
the idea of God.

00:35:41.262 --> 00:35:43.220
Because that's where
people get really hung up.

00:35:43.220 --> 00:35:45.450
It's the god of
their grandfathers,

00:35:45.450 --> 00:35:50.040
or it's a judgmental old man
on a cloud with a beard who's

00:35:50.040 --> 00:35:53.260
really judgmental and
scowling and disapproving,

00:35:53.260 --> 00:35:57.590
and hates people of this faith
and loves people of the other.

00:35:57.590 --> 00:36:03.530
But for me it was when
I started researching

00:36:03.530 --> 00:36:06.730
Native American
spirituality, and I

00:36:06.730 --> 00:36:09.150
found this concept
of Wakan Tanka

00:36:09.150 --> 00:36:11.480
from the Lakota
Sioux idea of God.

00:36:11.480 --> 00:36:13.180
And the name
literally translates

00:36:13.180 --> 00:36:15.300
as "the great mystery."

00:36:15.300 --> 00:36:17.210
And when I started
thinking about God

00:36:17.210 --> 00:36:22.020
as the great mystery--
sure, a creator,

00:36:22.020 --> 00:36:26.730
sure, all-loving, sure, running
through this material realm

00:36:26.730 --> 00:36:29.590
and running through science
and infinite other dimensions.

00:36:29.590 --> 00:36:32.440
But when I think about
it is the great mystery,

00:36:32.440 --> 00:36:34.550
and that god is
essentially unknowable,

00:36:34.550 --> 00:36:36.150
that helps me a lot.

00:36:36.150 --> 00:36:40.070
So I don't I don't know who
or what god is specifically,

00:36:40.070 --> 00:36:43.380
but that was a really
helpful bridge for me.

00:36:46.859 --> 00:36:48.900
AUDIENCE: You've played
a number of unique roles.

00:36:48.900 --> 00:36:50.400
I mean, I loved you
on "The Office,"

00:36:50.400 --> 00:36:53.022
but I really also liked you
on "Six Feet Under" as well.

00:36:53.022 --> 00:36:54.980
I was wondering if there
was something specific

00:36:54.980 --> 00:37:00.090
that you look for when you're
considering taking on a role.

00:37:00.090 --> 00:37:02.600
RAINN WILSON: It's kind of
this way for all actors--

00:37:02.600 --> 00:37:04.060
do you respond to it?

00:37:04.060 --> 00:37:06.090
You read the role,
and does it just

00:37:06.090 --> 00:37:07.540
touch you or move
you in some way?

00:37:07.540 --> 00:37:09.290
Does it affect you?

00:37:11.990 --> 00:37:14.270
Part of what the book is
about, "The Bassoon King,"

00:37:14.270 --> 00:37:18.440
is why I always play
these weird outsiders,

00:37:18.440 --> 00:37:21.680
and I'm really drawn to playing
these weird, outsider roles.

00:37:21.680 --> 00:37:25.860
I wouldn't know how to play a
popular guy, or a well-balanced

00:37:25.860 --> 00:37:28.170
individual.

00:37:28.170 --> 00:37:29.610
I don't connect.

00:37:29.610 --> 00:37:31.810
I don't know how to do it.

00:37:31.810 --> 00:37:35.327
Actually, I'd like to try
some time to see if I could.

00:37:35.327 --> 00:37:36.910
That would be really
difficult for me.

00:37:36.910 --> 00:37:40.520
So it is a kind of
an instinct thing.

00:37:45.019 --> 00:37:47.310
As you've been acting for
many years, you kind of know.

00:37:47.310 --> 00:37:49.121
Maybe it's the same
in the tech world,

00:37:49.121 --> 00:37:51.120
if you're offered a
challenge in the tech world,

00:37:51.120 --> 00:37:53.617
and you're kind of like,
oh, I like that challenge.

00:37:53.617 --> 00:37:54.700
And I know how to do that.

00:37:54.700 --> 00:37:56.430
I don't know specifically
how to do it,

